<subSubSection id="AD7E81A42D497AEC59B16DF879D332D4" pageId="63" pageNumber="63" type="description">
<paragraph id="9F8CC774F373F1151DE463AEDF196EE6" pageId="63" pageNumber="63">Worker. Length 2 1/4 lines.-Black: clothed with pale golden pubescence. Thorax: a very stout acute spine at each angle of the anterior margin of the thorax; the mesothorax convex above, the sides swollen; the metathorax with two divergent stout acute spines; the scale of the abdomen quadrate, with two long, rather slender spines above, which curve backwards over the abdomen; the legs without spines or pubescence, the calcaria pale testaceous.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="DC933A772674F16B77FF314922FB90FE" pageId="63" pageNumber="63" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="6963D478FD03138982BF541B9188E49E" pageId="63" pageNumber="63">Hab. Burmah.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="08D13AD0E57CBC4784E54EB37C42C857" pageId="63" pageNumber="63" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="32F7B3BCDC4286FBE64EEC794499494B" pageId="63" pageNumber="63">
This species is very like 
<taxonomicName id="F5B0CBF09249699F0AE77E86F240E645" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:34522" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Polyrhachis" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Polyrhachis dives Smith" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="63" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dives">P. dives</taxonomicName>
from Singapore, but differs principally in the form of the mesothorax.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
